ook explores the ideals and institutions through which Middle Eastern societies—from the rise of Islam in the seventh century C.E. to the present day—have confronted poverty and the poor. By introducing new sources and presenting familiar ones with new questions, the contributors examine ideas about poverty and the poor, ideals and practices of charity, and state and private initiatives of poor relief over this extensive time span. They avoid easy generalizations about Islam and the Middle East as they seek to set the ideals and practices in comparative perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCharityvCongresses. 0aCharityzMiddle EastvCongresses. 0aIslamxCharitiesvCongresses. 0aPovertyzMiddle EastvCongresses. 4aBusiness and Economics : Economy and Society. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Philanthropy & Charity.2bisacsh1 aBaron, Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonner, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonner, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCohen, Mark R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Juan R.I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEner, Mine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEner, Mine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGinio, Eyal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoexter, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuran, Timur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLibal, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMattson, Ingrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSabra, Adam, econtrib